JavaScript Object Constructors:

#) Object Constructor Functions:
    - Sometimes we need to create many objects of the same type.
    - To create an object type we use an object constructor function.
    - It is considered good practice to name constructor functions with an upper-case first letter.

        eg: object type person

            function Person(first, last, age, eye) {
                this.firstName = first;
                this.lastName = last;
                this.age = age;
                this.eyeColor = eye;
            }

            Now we can use new Person() to create many new Person objects:
    
    - ‚ö†Ô∏è In the constructor function, this has no value.
    - ‚ö†Ô∏è The value of this will become the new object when a new object is created.

        // constructor function for Person objects
        function Person(first, last, age, city) {
            this.firstName = first;
            this.lastName = last;
            this.age = age;
            this.city = city;
        }

        // create a Person object
        const asian = new Person("Kim", "Jung", 45, "Seoul");
        const indian = new Person("Ram", "Gupta", 55, "Delhi");

        // Display property
        document.getElementById("1").innerHTML = `He is ${asian.firstName} from ${asian.city}.`;
        document.getElementById("2").innerHTML = `He is ${indian.firstName} from ${indian.city}.`;

        o/p:    He is Kim from Seoul.
                He is Ram from Delhi.


#) Property Default Values:
    - A value given to a property will be a default value for all objects created by the constructor:

        function Person(first, last, age, city) {
            this.firstName = first;
            this.lastName = last;
            this.age = age;
            this.city = city;
            this.planet = "Earth";
        }

        const asian = new Person("Kim", "Jung", 45, "Seoul");
        const indian = new Person("Ram", "Gupta", 55, "Delhi");

        document.getElementById("1").innerHTML =
            `He is ${asian.firstName} from ${asian.city} in planet ${asian.planet}.`;
        document.getElementById("2").innerHTML =
            `He is ${indian.firstName} from ${indian.city} in plane ${indian.planet}.`;
        
        o/p:    He is Kim from Seoul in planet Earth.
                He is Ram from Delhi in plane Earth.


#) Adding a Property to an Object:
    - adding property is similar to adding property in regular object.

        asian.eye = "brown";
        document.getElementById("4").innerHTML =
            `${asian.firstName} from ${asian.city} has a ${asian.eye} eye.`;

    - ‚ö†Ô∏è The new peoperty eye will be added to the asian object only. Not to any other Person
        objects.


#) Adding a Property to a Constructor:
    - ‚ùå You can NOT add a new property to an object constructor:

        Person.language = "Hindi";  // ‚ùå does not work. undefined
        document.getElementById("5").innerHTML =
            `${indian.firstName} from ${indian.city} speaks ${indian.language}.`;

        o/p:    Ram from Delhi speaks undefined.
    
    - ‚úÖ To add a new property, you must add it to the constructor function prototype:

        Person.prototype.language = "Hindi";  // ‚úÖ works but  language will have a default value Hindi
        asian.language = "Korean";  // overriding 

        document.getElementById("6").innerHTML =
            `${indian.firstName} from ${indian.city} speaks ${indian.language}.`;
        document.getElementById("7").innerHTML =
            `${asian.firstName} from ${asian.city} speaks ${asian.language}.`;


----------------------------------- WITH METHODS ---------------------------------------------------------


#) Constructor Function Methods:
    - A constructor function can also have methods:

        function Person(first, last, age, city) {
            this.firstName = first;
            this.lastName = last;
            this.age = age;
            this.city = city;
            this.fullName = function(){
                return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
            };
        }

        const asian = new Person("Kim", "Jung", 45, "Seoul");
        const indian = new Person("Ram", "Gupta", 55, "Delhi");
        
        document.getElementById("1").innerHTML =`His name is  ${asian.fullName()}.`;

        o/p: His name is Kim Jung.


#) Adding a Method to an Object:
    - similar to adding method to a regular object.

        // adding new method 'bio' to an object asian
        asian.bio = function() {
            return `Hi i am ${this.firstName} from ${this.city}.`;
        }
        // adding a new method 'changeLastName' with parameter lName
        asian.changeLastName = function(lName) {
            this.lastName = lName;
        }
        // changing name by calling method with argument
        asian.changeLastName("Yung");

        document.getElementById("2").innerHTML = asian.bio();
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = `His name is  ${asian.fullName()}.`;

        o/p:    Hi i am Kim from Seoul.
                His name is Kim Yung.
    
    - ‚ö†Ô∏è The new method will be added to asian. Not to any other Person Objects.


#) Adding a Method to a Constructor:
    - ‚ùå You cannot add a new method to an object constructor function.

        // adding a new method 'changeFirstName' with parameter fName to object constructor
        Person.changeFirstName = function (fName) {  // TypeError: indian.changeFirstName is not a function.
            this.firstName = fName;
        }
        // changing name by calling method with argument
        indian.changeFirstName("Manoj");
        document.getElementById("4").innerHTML = `His name is  ${indian.fullName()}.`;  
    
    - ‚úÖ Adding a new method to a constructor must be done to the constructor function prototype:

        Person.prototype.changeFirstName = function (fName) {
            this.firstName = fName;
        }

        indian.changeFirstName("Manoj");

        document.getElementById("5").innerHTML = `His name is  ${indian.fullName()}.`;  
        // ‚úÖ His name is Manoj Gupta.
    
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


#) Built-in JavaScript Constructors:
    - JavaScript has built-in constructors for all native objects:

        new Object()   // A new Object object
        new Array()    // A new Array object
        new Map()      // A new Map object
        new Set()      // A new Set object
        new Date()     // A new Date object
        new RegExp()   // A new RegExp object
        new Function() // A new Function object
    
    - üí° The Math() object is not in the list. Math is a global object. The new keyword cannot be
        used on Math.



üß†üß† Did You Know?

    üëâ Use object literals {} instead of new Object().

    üëâ Use array literals [] instead of new Array().

    üëâ Use pattern literals /()/ instead of new RegExp().

    üëâ Use function expressions () {} instead of new Function().